SUMMARIZER="K"> 

In terms of magnitude, Chile is the world's most seismic country.  It
has a coastline of 2,270 miles along the "ring of fire," between the
Nacza and South American plates.  A 1985, 7.1 Richter Scale earthquake
was comparable to the San Francisco quake.  But a 1960 quake of 9.5
destroyed Valparaiso.  Parts of the coast dropped nine feet and 5,000
people were killed. A tsunami followed, killing others.

Chilean engineers design their buildings of reinforced concrete.  They
do not rock during earthquakes, and since these codes were adopted in
1930, only three engineered buildings have collapsed.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d57"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890228-0019"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K"> 

Last year's Armenian earthquake, with 25,000 killed, (13,000 injured
and half a million homeless) brought the earth's yearly death total to
its highest since 1976, when 10 times many died in a Chinese
earthquake.  2,000 more died in other quakes last year.

The geological survey reported 61 significant quakes last year,
including sites on the Nepal-Burma border, the Nepal-India border and
the Burma-China border.  The United States recorded three significant
quakes, in the Gulf of Alaska, Whittier and Pasadena, California.
Canada had one; Europe, Africa and Japan also recorded relatively
minor quakes.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d57"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891028-0022"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K"> 

The Solomon Islands experienced an earthquake at 8:05 p.m. today,
measuring 7.2 on the Richter scale.  There were no immediate reports
of injury or damage, not surprising since the area is sparsely
populated and minimally developed.  No tsunami was reported.  This was
the strongest quake reported in the world in the last five months; the
epicenter was placed on Guadacanal Island.

The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on seismographs.
Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude.
That means a reading of 7.5 shows an earthquake ten times stronger
than a quake of 6.5.</SUM>

<SUM
